{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/nlp-data-apps-batteries-included-with-streamlit-and-huggingface-828083a89bb2", "time": 1683014113.83923, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/nlp-data-apps-batteries-included-with-streamlit-and-huggingface-828083a89bb2/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "NLP Data Apps: Batteries Included with Streamlit and HuggingFace | by Andrea Guidi | Towards Data Science", "h1": "NLP Data Apps: Batteries Included with Streamlit and HuggingFace", "description": "When building a data science project, one of the last tasks (but not last for importance) that needs to be done is the implementation of a front-end, which makes the model available to the end-users\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["When building a data science project, one of the last tasks (but not last for importance) that needs to be done is the implementation of a front-end, which makes the model available to the end-users and abstracts them from all the machinery that lies below the user interface.", "The common ways of doing this are:", "If you don\u2019t really like messing with JS frameworks (like me) or want to be able to build a true end-to-end pipeline, then you must use Streamlit at least once.", "Streamlit, as the website says, is the fastest way to build data apps. And, while it may sound arrogant, it could never be anything more than true.", "To show how fast it can be to get hands dirty, I built a prototype with Streamlit and HuggingFace\u2019s Transformers, using a pre-trained Question Answering model.", "Yeah, I said \u2018batteries included\u2019, but you gotta buy them first!", "Open a terminal (or an Anaconda prompt, depending on your choice) and run:", "Once the installation is done, grab your editor and first import the necessary packages:", "This allows you to use pre-trained HuggingFace models as I don\u2019t want to train one from scratch. Then, you can build a function to load the model; notice that I used the @st.cache() decorator to avoid reloading the model each time (at least it should help reducing some overhead, but I gotta dive deeper into Streamlit\u2019s beautiful documentation):", "Add a header and some text to fill some white gaps together with a sidebar:", "Given the fact that I chose a question answering model, I have to provide a text cell for writing the question and a text area to copy the text that serves as a context to look the answer in. This can be done in two lines:", "Now you can call the model to answer the deepest and hardest questions of the universe. To avoid errors when first loading the app, I wrapped the inference code inside an if statement (totally bad code, must admit it):", "And this will output the answer to the question you asked about something in the text you provided.The full code here:", "To run the script, just type: streamlit run script__name.py and it will run by default on localhost:8501, so open it in your browser.Here a screenshot of the output:", "This is not meant of course to represent an exhaustive guide for every feature of Streamlit, but it\u2019s just a way to let others know this great tool in the way I did, by experimenting.", "Thanks, and goodbye until next time!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I love data, machine learning and Autoencoders. Control systems/electronic engineer."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F828083a89bb2&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fnlp-data-apps-batteries-included-with-streamlit-and-huggingface-828083a89bb2&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?op